Data Vizualization and Interpolation of Missing Values¶

To interpolate missing values in the columns with numeric data it is important to decide if we should replace it with 0, median, or mean. But as data contains values for Temp, Rainfall etc it would be incorrect to do so as it will change the probability distribution of varibles. If the data contains outliers it would be better to replace it with median else mean would be good option

In [10]:
for col in csv_data.columns:
    if csv_data[col].dtypes == np.float64:
        print(col , min(csv_data[col]), max(csv_data[col]))
        sb.boxplot(x=col, data = csv_data)
        plt.show()

Data preprocessing¶

The K-means Clustering Algorithm, HAC, and Decision Tree all work on Numeric Data. Thus, it is important to create dummy variables or one hot encoders for categorical data.

Also, the data in the numeric columns have large differences in ranges. As K-means is a distance based algorithm large values can cause greater distances even if the instances belong to the same cluster thus, it would be better to scale the Numeric values

To test the overfitting data for a particular model the data has been split into training dataset and testing dataset.

In [18]:
y = csv_data['RainTomorrow']
X = csv_data.drop(['RainTomorrow'],axis=1)
le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(y)
y = pd.Series(y)
X_train, X_test , y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.3,stratify =y)
num_features = [x for x in X.columns if csv_data[x].dtypes==np.float64]
cat_features = [x for x in X.columns if csv_data[x].dtypes!=np.float64]
categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[("ohe",OneHotEncoder(sparse = False,handle_unknown='ignore'))])
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[("mms",MinMaxScaler())])
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numeric_transformer, num_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, cat_features)])
In [19]:
X_train =preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test =preprocessor.transform(X_test)

After data transformation there are a total of 89 features in the training dataset. Not all of them are important in predicting clusters. Aditionally, K-means being a distance based algoritm might not perform well dummy data. So it is important to perform Dimensionality Reduction and thus, transform data using PCA. After combinations of feature values I found out that kmeans performs best with 13 features and thus 13 features have been selected

In [20]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
pca = PCA(n_components =13)
pca.fit(X_train)
X_train_c = pca.transform(X_train)
X_test_c = pca.transform(X_test)

The Hyperparameters for K-means models n_init :Number of time the k-means algorithm will be run with different centroid seeds and max_iter: Maximum number of iterations of the k-means algorithm for a single run

HAC Clustering¶

A dendogram plot to visualize clusters

In [25]:
import scipy.cluster.hierarchy as shc

plt.figure(figsize=(50, 20))
plt.title("Customer Dendograms")
dend = shc.dendrogram(shc.linkage(X_train_c, method='ward'))

The Hyperparameters for HCA clustering was the affinity and linkage which is eucledian in default case and have been tuned to l1 norm and complete to test if the model perfroms better. complete or maximum linkage uses the maximum distances between all observations of the two sets.ward minimizes the variance of the clusters being merged.

In [26]:
hac_ward = AgglomerativeClustering()
hac_ward.fit(X_train_c,y_train)

hac_complete = AgglomerativeClustering(affinity="l1",linkage="complete")
hac_complete.fit(X_train_c,y_train)


print("Training Accuracy for ward method:",fowlkes_mallows_score(hac_ward.fit_predict(X_train_c),y_train))
print("Training Accuracy for complete method:",fowlkes_mallows_score(hac_complete.fit_predict((X_train_c)),y_train))

Training Accuracy for ward method: 0.5864230243243818
Training Accuracy for complete method: 0.5284671565605606
In [27]:
print("Testing Accuracy for ward method:",fowlkes_mallows_score(hac_ward.fit_predict(X_test_c),y_test))
print("Testing Accuracy for complete method:",fowlkes_mallows_score(hac_complete.fit_predict((X_test_c)),y_test))

Testing Accuracy for ward method: 0.5874495656773543
Testing Accuracy for complete method: 0.6182978013390411

We can use Unsupervised Learning Algorithms such as K Means Clustering and Hirerarchical clustering as prediction algorithms. We can divide the data into clusters equal to the number of classes. For these algorithms I have used fowlkes_mallows_scorewhich is the geometric mean between of the precision and recall. FMI = TP / sqrt((TP + FP) * (TP + FN))

Decision Tree¶

It is not imporatant to perform PCA on decision tree model thus, the training data used for DT contains all 89 features

In [28]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier()

The hyperparameters used for Decision Tree are criterion: Measure the quality of split based on either i. or entropy,for information gained min_samples_split: The min number of instances present to split a node, max_depth: The maximum depth of the tree, min_samples_leaf : Min number of instances present for leaf nodes and max_leaf_nodes: The maximum number of parent nodes in the tree

In [29]:

Model Performance comparision¶

It is clearly evident that both the clustering algorithms K-means and HAC have low training accuracy i.e. they are underfitting and low testing accuracy signifies overfitting. While the Decision Tree model is neither underfitting nor overfitting
